{
  "doc_id": "822",
  "text": "The fusion pore expansion rate is sensitive to a concentration of intracellular free calcium ([Ca 2ϩ ] i ) in the micromolar range (Fernández-Chacón and Alvarez 4340 © Oxford University Press [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . As the binding of Ca 2ϩ ions to free phospholipid headgroups is negligible below 10 µM free Ca 2ϩ , it has been suggested that pore expansion may involve more than lipidic interactions within membranes. Thus, although it is generally accepted that fusion pore expansion involves lipid incorporation [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , even this lipidic state of pore expansion may be regulated by proteins [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . However, it has also been shown that significant Ca 2ϩ binding, at even lower free concentrations, does occur between phosphatidylserine headgroups of closely apposed lamellae [CITATION_8] . As comparable domains might be present around early fusion pores during their initial expansion, it cannot be ruled out that the effect of Ca 2ϩ in the physiological range might also involve this type of Ca 2ϩ binding between anionic lipids. Whereas the possible contributions of such domains are difficult to test for, the involvement of proteins can be examined readily using a variety of agents known to modify protein function in specific ways.",
